02:16:04.610 --> 02:16:05.910
Congratulations.

02:16:05.910 --> 02:16:07.710
Come on up.

02:16:07.710 --> 02:16:13.430
There he is All right.

02:16:23.090 --> 02:16:25.330
&gt;&gt; Allister Chang: --
Be with you all today.

02:16:25.330 --> 02:16:28.870
I will also start with
a quick story of my own.

02:16:28.870 --> 02:16:32.760
My parents immigrated to the
US and worked in restaurants.

02:16:32.760 --> 02:16:37.810
And for me, the library was the
bridge between the Chinese home

02:16:37.810 --> 02:16:42.840
that I had and the American
English speaking world outside.

02:16:42.840 --> 02:16:49.850
And for me, the library has been
so important in shifting my life

02:16:49.850 --> 02:16:55.630
to be the first person in my
family to go to college and be able

02:16:55.630 --> 02:16:59.360
to choose what kind of
life I wanted to live.

02:16:59.360 --> 02:17:04.090
I'm here today to tell you
about Libraries Without Borders

02:17:04.090 --> 02:17:10.640
and specifically about the Ideas
Box which was earlier mentioned.

02:17:10.640 --> 02:17:18.930
And the story begins in 2010
when I joined the organization

02:17:18.930 --> 02:17:22.390
and we were working
in Haiti at the time.

02:17:22.390 --> 02:17:27.620 position:56%
And after a 7.0 magnitude earthquake
that destroyed the library

02:17:27.620 --> 02:17:32.140
that we had hoped to build, our
local partners asked us to stay.

02:17:32.140 --> 02:17:36.340
And at the time we asked ourselves,

02:17:36.340 --> 02:17:39.450
is this really the right
time to rebuild the library?

02:17:39.450 --> 02:17:43.490
Should resources not first to be
spent on food, water, and shelter?

02:17:43.490 --> 02:17:49.620
At the insistence of University
of Haiti, we went and we worked.

02:17:49.620 --> 02:17:53.790
And it was in this project that
we learned an important lesson

02:17:53.790 --> 02:17:56.760
that shaped the story of
our organization's future.

02:17:57.890 --> 02:18:03.850 position:56%
Informational tools and spaces are
critical for disaster relief efforts

02:18:03.850 --> 02:18:07.870
and should not be relegated
for many years later.

02:18:08.880 --> 02:18:11.740
In humanitarian contexts,
we often focus

02:18:11.740 --> 02:18:14.850
on basic needs, food,
water, shelter.

02:18:14.850 --> 02:18:19.600
But we saw on the ground was
that people need more than that

02:18:19.600 --> 02:18:22.250
in order to build their futures.

02:18:23.450 --> 02:18:27.570
Our library in Haiti became a hub
for community leaders, engineers,

02:18:27.570 --> 02:18:30.600
and aid workers to
reference reliable information

02:18:30.600 --> 02:18:33.550
and to develop collaborations.

02:18:33.550 --> 02:18:37.470 position:56%
Today, Libraries Without Borders has
expanded upon that what we learned

02:18:37.470 --> 02:18:41.940
in Haiti to leverage informational
tools for disaster relief,

02:18:41.940 --> 02:18:46.360
peace building, entrepreneurship,
and economic development,

02:18:46.360 --> 02:18:51.080
and the foundation of all
that is literacy programming.

02:18:52.130 --> 02:18:56.410 position:56%
Recognizing our work with internally
displaced persons in a Haiti,

02:18:56.410 --> 02:18:58.650
we received requests from partners,

02:18:58.650 --> 02:19:03.090
from UNHCR in the African
Great Lakes first.

02:19:03.090 --> 02:19:08.230 position:56%
And that's where we started to
continue the story of the Ideas Box.

02:19:08.230 --> 02:19:11.450
And so, does anyone here know
what the average length of stay

02:19:11.450 --> 02:19:15.220
for a refugee in a campus today?

02:19:15.220 --> 02:19:16.520
Shout out some numbers.

02:19:16.520 --> 02:19:23.510
Oh. There's supposed
to be a question mark.

02:19:23.510 --> 02:19:26.660
[ Laughter ]

02:19:26.660 --> 02:19:32.280
Ruined the surprise, but it's, you
know, whether or not you-- it's a--

02:19:32.280 --> 02:19:36.620
this number is-- for us,
was heart breaking to learn

02:19:36.620 --> 02:19:39.770
that this is the length of
stay for an average refugee

02:19:39.770 --> 02:19:41.990
in a protracted crisis today.

02:19:41.990 --> 02:19:46.150
And when-- you know, when we first
started this work, people said,

02:19:46.150 --> 02:19:48.450
what-- exactly what we had asked
in Haiti at that time which was,

02:19:48.450 --> 02:19:51.190
is this the right time
to this kind of work?

02:19:51.190 --> 02:19:54.320
And they said, you know,
these are temporary spaces.

02:19:54.320 --> 02:19:58.550
If it's 26 years, we're
losing generations of kids.

02:19:58.550 --> 02:20:02.550
They're no longer temporary spaces.

02:20:02.550 --> 02:20:08.740
So today, you know, there are
over 65 million refugees and IDPs.

02:20:08.740 --> 02:20:10.480
And UNICEF recently
estimated that there are

02:20:10.480 --> 02:20:14.180
over 28 million child refugees.

02:20:14.180 --> 02:20:15.880
For us, it was to address
this challenge

02:20:15.880 --> 02:20:19.630
that we approached Philippe
Starck, the French designer,

02:20:19.630 --> 02:20:21.440
who worked with us to design a kit.

02:20:21.440 --> 02:20:26.780
And he said to us when he agreed
to help us that he wanted to--

02:20:26.780 --> 02:20:30.570
he was engaged by our mission to
not only help people stay alive,

02:20:30.570 --> 02:20:33.920
but actually help them to live.

02:20:36.250 --> 02:20:39.630
And so, we built the Ideas Box

02:20:39.630 --> 02:20:43.340
which is a pop-up multimedia
center unpacked in 20 minutes.

02:20:43.340 --> 02:20:46.810
That is fully autonomous,
portable, and durable.

02:20:46.810 --> 02:20:53.840
And we have a quick video to show
that explains what this box does.

02:20:57.510 --> 02:22:14.510
[ Music ]

02:22:14.510 --> 02:22:24.620
[ Applause ]

02:22:24.620 --> 02:22:28.180
So for us, most of our
work is with local partners

02:22:28.180 --> 02:22:32.700
to customize all the Ideas Box
contents including paper books,

02:22:32.700 --> 02:22:36.010
eReaders and dozens
of educational apps.

02:22:36.010 --> 02:22:38.960
And each Ideas Box
serves 10,000 people

02:22:38.960 --> 02:22:40.960
and quickly becomes
a learning center,

02:22:40.960 --> 02:22:43.730
a library, and a community hub.

02:22:45.310 --> 02:22:49.850
After 30 months of experimentation
in the humanitarian context,

02:22:49.850 --> 02:22:52.990
we have had qualitative and
quantitative evaluations done

02:22:52.990 --> 02:22:57.150
that demonstrate the impact
of the Ideas Box in education,

02:22:57.150 --> 02:23:00.600
community building, and
psychosocial support.

02:23:00.600 --> 02:23:05.050
The first two units of the Ideas
Box were implemented in Haiti

02:23:05.050 --> 02:23:08.090
where we registered 24,000
visits in three months

02:23:08.090 --> 02:23:11.060
and around 3,300 unique users.

02:23:11.060 --> 02:23:15.950
A few months ago, we conducted a
quantitative study assessing the

02:23:15.950 --> 02:23:18.950
educational literacy
and numeracy outcomes

02:23:18.950 --> 02:23:20.860
of the Ideas Box through NRCT.

02:23:20.860 --> 02:23:25.080
And it showed a 23% higher
average academic improvement

02:23:25.080 --> 02:23:28.650
in the test group compared
with the control group as well

02:23:28.650 --> 02:23:33.070
as increased curiosity
and participation.

02:23:33.070 --> 02:23:35.840
We recognize the importance
of replicating the study

02:23:35.840 --> 02:23:39.960
in different contexts and
with larger sample sizes.

02:23:39.960 --> 02:23:42.400
But, you know, this initial
result is interesting

02:23:42.400 --> 02:23:46.150
because it helps us claim
the impact of the Ideas Box

02:23:46.150 --> 02:23:49.020
and how it exceeds
the sum of its pieces.

02:23:49.020 --> 02:23:52.210
We're learning how educational
outcomes are not just the result

02:23:52.210 --> 02:23:55.150
of the quality of teacher and
the quality of curriculum,

02:23:55.150 --> 02:23:57.400
but also the quality
of the physical space.

02:23:57.400 --> 02:24:00.460
And teachers have told us
that moving their class

02:24:00.460 --> 02:24:04.120
to the Ideas Box classroom has
fundamentally shifted dynamics

02:24:04.120 --> 02:24:08.100
between students and
fostered group discussions

02:24:08.100 --> 02:24:11.050
and more interactive
learning opportunities.

02:24:11.050 --> 02:24:15.190
And it is with sharing the results
of the program with refugees

02:24:15.190 --> 02:24:18.160
that local governments and
libraries began suggesting

02:24:18.160 --> 02:24:24.960
that we run programs and other
contexts including in The Bronx,

02:24:24.960 --> 02:24:30.990
in Saxel, in France and
in Queensland Australia.

02:24:30.990 --> 02:24:34.100
In the US, we partnered with
the New York Public Library

02:24:34.100 --> 02:24:37.590
to create pop-up library
spaces and Laundromats

02:24:37.590 --> 02:24:41.980
where we facilitated storytelling
and literacy workshops for children

02:24:41.980 --> 02:24:45.230
and resume workshops for
adults who are waiting

02:24:45.230 --> 02:24:48.030
for their laundry to wash and dry.

02:24:48.030 --> 02:24:51.970
We've also partnered with the
National Library Colombia recently

02:24:51.970 --> 02:24:55.430
to leverage ICT tools for peace
building in the rural areas

02:24:55.430 --> 02:25:00.500 position:56%
that have been most affected by
last 52 years of guerrilla conflict.

02:25:00.500 --> 02:25:02.820
And my time is up.

02:25:02.820 --> 02:25:07.640
And our next step is to formalize
micro entrepreneurship models

02:25:07.640 --> 02:25:10.420
to sustainably grow
the Ideas Box program.

02:25:10.420 --> 02:25:12.400
We have 70 in the field right now.

02:25:12.400 --> 02:25:15.520
And our goal is to
build 1,000 by 2020.

02:25:15.520 --> 02:25:17.320
Thank you.

02:25:17.320 --> 02:25:24.620
[ Applause ]

02:25:24.620 --> 02:25:25.920
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: Wow.

02:25:25.920 --> 02:25:28.010
Thank you, Allister.

02:25:28.010 --> 02:25:34.780
And finally, the winner
of the Rubenstein Prize,

02:25:34.780 --> 02:25:39.280
Reading Rockets represented
by Noel Gunther.

02:25:39.280 --> 02:25:43.320
Reading Rockets was created
by WETA to address the need

02:25:43.320 --> 02:25:47.290
for evidence-based resources
among literacy providers,

02:25:47.290 --> 02:25:49.990
educators and parents.

02:25:49.990 --> 02:25:55.530
Their website is accessed nearly 6
millions times a year by parents,

02:25:55.530 --> 02:26:00.250
teachers, and caregivers in need
of literacy resources and all

02:26:00.250 --> 02:26:02.450
of the resources are free.

02:26:02.450 --> 02:26:06.070
Thank you Reading Rockets
and congratulations.

02:26:06.070 --> 02:26:09.510
Come on up.

02:26:09.510 --> 02:26:18.350
[ Applause ]

02:26:18.350 --> 02:26:20.100
&gt;&gt; Noel Gunther: Thanks
so much Dr. Hayden.

02:26:20.100 --> 02:26:23.190
Thanks to you Pam Jackson, all
of your colleagues at the library

02:26:23.190 --> 02:26:25.450
and Mr. Rubenstein for this award.

02:26:25.450 --> 02:26:28.060
We're enormously grateful.

02:26:28.060 --> 02:26:29.490
My parents were immigrants too.

02:26:29.490 --> 02:26:31.730
That's seems to be theme today.

02:26:31.730 --> 02:26:34.140
And everything they accomplished
and everything I've been able

02:26:34.140 --> 02:26:38.170
to do really began with one
thing which was learning to read.

02:26:38.170 --> 02:26:42.080
At Reading Rockets, we look at
how young children learn to read,

02:26:42.080 --> 02:26:47.410
why so many kids struggle, and most
important, what can we do about it.

02:26:47.410 --> 02:26:49.460
I'll tell you our story
in just a moment.

02:26:49.460 --> 02:26:51.470
By that, we like to
start with a video clip,

02:26:51.470 --> 02:26:55.520
a short clip from a documentary
we produced for PBS called "A Tale

02:26:55.520 --> 02:26:58.960
of Two Schools" narrated
by Morgan Freeman.

02:26:58.960 --> 02:27:02.870
We spent a whole year inside two
struggling elementary schools.

02:27:02.870 --> 02:27:06.580
One in Mississippi Delta,
and one in Fort Worth, Texas.

02:27:06.580 --> 02:27:07.880
And here's how the show begins.

02:27:07.880 --> 02:27:09.180
&gt;&gt; [Background Music] Shhhh.

02:27:09.180 --> 02:27:10.500
I'm the teacher.

02:27:10.500 --> 02:27:13.990
&gt;&gt; This is Tavares.

02:27:13.990 --> 02:27:18.010
He's starting first grade
in Fort Worth, Texas.

02:27:18.010 --> 02:27:21.400
He needs to learn how to read,
but he's already way behind.

02:27:21.400 --> 02:27:23.700
&gt;&gt; He will probably struggle
for the rest of his life

02:27:23.700 --> 02:27:26.670
if we don't work on it now.

02:27:26.670 --> 02:27:28.870
&gt;&gt; Meanwhile, in Sumner,
Mississippi,

02:27:28.870 --> 02:27:31.770
rookie teacher Jill Todd
faces her own challenge.

02:27:31.770 --> 02:27:33.440 position:56%
Trying to teach reading in a setting

02:27:33.440 --> 02:27:36.030
where almost every child
needs a lot of help.

02:27:36.030 --> 02:27:38.960
&gt;&gt; I'm worn out, just
extremely tired.

02:27:38.960 --> 02:27:41.510
&gt;&gt; And the superintendent
is at the end of his rope.

02:27:41.510 --> 02:27:44.560
&gt;&gt; So, hell, if they won't give us
decent books, how are we supposed

02:27:44.560 --> 02:27:46.330
to improve our test scores?

02:27:46.330 --> 02:27:48.550
&gt;&gt; Across the country,
schools are struggling

02:27:48.550 --> 02:27:52.730
with their most basic job,
teaching kids to read.

02:27:52.730 --> 02:27:55.850
We spent an entire year inside
two schools that have known a lot

02:27:55.850 --> 02:27:58.890
of failure and are now
trying valiantly to improve.

02:27:58.890 --> 02:28:00.570
&gt;&gt; There are a lot of
times I want to quit.

02:28:00.570 --> 02:28:03.430
&gt;&gt; I think we alternated
between chaos and limbo.

02:28:03.430 --> 02:28:05.470
&gt;&gt; All kid can learn.

02:28:05.470 --> 02:28:07.340
All kids can be successful.

02:28:07.340 --> 02:28:10.140
&gt;&gt; What does it really take
to turn our schools around?

02:28:10.140 --> 02:28:12.960
And what happens if we fail?

02:28:12.960 --> 02:28:14.450
&gt;&gt; These kids deserve better.

02:28:14.450 --> 02:28:18.070
And if these kids don't
get an adequate education,

02:28:18.070 --> 02:28:20.510
they will not do better.

02:28:20.510 --> 02:28:41.450
[ Music ]

02:28:41.450 --> 02:28:43.810
&gt;&gt; Noel Gunther: That
year changed my life.

02:28:43.810 --> 02:28:47.340
And that short his captures
the three-core ideas behind

02:28:47.340 --> 02:28:48.940
Reading Rockets.

02:28:48.940 --> 02:28:51.800
First, too many children
are failing.

02:28:51.800 --> 02:28:54.510
One third of our fourth
graders scored below basic

02:28:54.510 --> 02:28:58.250
on their NATE test which means they
can't understand a simple story

02:28:58.250 --> 02:29:00.310
or they can barely read it all.

02:29:00.310 --> 02:29:02.670
That just can't be OK.

02:29:02.670 --> 02:29:04.920
Second, teachers are overwhelmed.

02:29:04.920 --> 02:29:06.230
They want to do a great job,

02:29:06.230 --> 02:29:08.300
but they often they
don't have the knowledge

02:29:08.300 --> 02:29:10.810
or the support that
they need to do it.

02:29:10.810 --> 02:29:15.510
And third and most important, we
know how to solve this problem.

02:29:15.510 --> 02:29:18.570
The federal government alone has
spent more than 2 billion dollars

02:29:18.570 --> 02:29:21.630
on reading research and
we know it's not easy.

02:29:21.630 --> 02:29:24.790
But if we follow that research
and if principles, teachers,

02:29:24.790 --> 02:29:26.530
and parents can work together,

02:29:26.530 --> 02:29:29.720
almost every child can
become a proficient reader,

02:29:29.720 --> 02:29:33.110
and that's where Reading
Rockets comes in.

02:29:33.110 --> 02:29:35.960
Reading Rockets is
all about solutions.

02:29:35.960 --> 02:29:39.100
We start with the best reading
research and then we use the power

02:29:39.100 --> 02:29:42.380
of media to show step by
step what each of us can do

02:29:42.380 --> 02:29:46.200
to help kids be more successful
as readers and writers.

02:29:46.200 --> 02:29:49.240
As a media company, we do
everything in all our power then

02:29:49.240 --> 02:29:52.600
to build a big audience and to
spread the words to parents,

02:29:52.600 --> 02:29:57.790
teachers and everyone else who
touches the life of a young child.

02:29:57.790 --> 02:30:00.900
When we started Reading
Rockets, my first question was,

02:30:00.900 --> 02:30:03.280
why do many kids struggle
with reading?

02:30:03.280 --> 02:30:07.640 position:56%
It turns out that our brains are
hardwired to master spoken language.

02:30:07.640 --> 02:30:09.770
Almost every child
learns to speak just

02:30:09.770 --> 02:30:11.980 position:56%
from being exposed to oral language.

02:30:11.980 --> 02:30:14.960
But we've only been
reading for 5,000 years,

02:30:14.960 --> 02:30:17.280
just a blink of an eye
in evolutionary terms.

02:30:17.280 --> 02:30:20.880
So to become a good reader,
you need to take brain circuits

02:30:20.880 --> 02:30:24.730 position:56%
that were originally designed for
spoken language and then rewire them

02:30:24.730 --> 02:30:26.790
to handle the printed word.

02:30:26.790 --> 02:30:30.050
And for many kids,
that is really hard.

02:30:30.050 --> 02:30:35.330 position:56%
And because it's so hard to learn
reading, it's also hard to teach it.

02:30:35.330 --> 02:30:37.580
Poor readers can be very
different one from another.

02:30:37.580 --> 02:30:40.680
You need to diagnose the problem
really carefully before you can

02:30:40.680 --> 02:30:41.980
solve it.

02:30:41.980 --> 02:30:45.770
Teaching reading is rocket science
said researcher Louisa Moats.

02:30:45.770 --> 02:30:49.070
And we see the best teachers,
they're great diagnosticians

02:30:49.070 --> 02:30:51.470
and may have a whole range
of strategies they can use

02:30:51.470 --> 02:30:54.390
to meet the kid-- needs
of individual kids.

02:30:54.390 --> 02:30:56.880
I saw all this firsthand
with my younger son, Aaron,

02:30:56.880 --> 02:31:00.900 position:56%
who seemed to have everything going
for him when he started first grade.

02:31:00.900 --> 02:31:03.090
Good vocabulary, lots
of background knowledge,

02:31:03.090 --> 02:31:05.560
hundreds of hours spent
listening to stories,

02:31:05.560 --> 02:31:09.020
and trust me unlimited
energy and enthusiasm.

02:31:09.020 --> 02:31:11.500
But none of that seemed to help
him when he got to second grade

02:31:11.500 --> 02:31:14.430
because his reading
was getting nowhere.

02:31:14.430 --> 02:31:17.790
And one night in our living room,
he threw a book up against the wall

02:31:17.790 --> 02:31:21.410
and he said, "I hate school" and
he started to cry and it was one

02:31:21.410 --> 02:31:24.670
of the most heartbreaking
moments of my life.

02:31:24.670 --> 02:31:28.000 position:56%
Thanks to Reading Rockets, I was in
an unusual position and we were able

02:31:28.000 --> 02:31:31.850
to find a great tutor who
figured out Aaron's problem

02:31:31.850 --> 02:31:33.150
and then worked diligently with him

02:31:33.150 --> 02:31:34.730
for almost a year until
it went away.

02:31:34.730 --> 02:31:39.210
But the sad truth is that Aaron is
an exception and the great majority

02:31:39.210 --> 02:31:43.970
of kids who fall behind in
school never managed to catch up.

02:31:43.970 --> 02:31:46.970
So, what can we do to help
solve the reading crisis?

02:31:46.970 --> 02:31:48.620
We started by asking the experts.

02:31:48.620 --> 02:31:52.580
It makes researchers and skilled
teachers knew the research insight.

02:31:52.580 --> 02:31:55.290
And now, they've spent a
lot of time in classrooms.

02:31:55.290 --> 02:31:58.350
We now offer engaging
in-depth interviews on video

02:31:58.350 --> 02:32:01.500
with the country's top experts
sharing their knowledge for free

02:32:01.500 --> 02:32:04.570
with anyone who comes to our side.

02:32:04.570 --> 02:32:07.860
We've also compiled a big growing
library of top-flight articles

02:32:07.860 --> 02:32:09.420
about teaching and reading.

02:32:09.420 --> 02:32:12.340
We start with really basic
information because we want

02:32:12.340 --> 02:32:14.260
to welcome everyone into the tent.

02:32:14.260 --> 02:32:17.860
But we also get very
detailed and granular.

02:32:17.860 --> 02:32:20.590 position:56%
So if you're concerned about a
second grader who's still struggling

02:32:20.590 --> 02:32:22.470
with her short vowel signs,

02:32:22.470 --> 02:32:25.570
we have good detailed
answers on Reading Rockets.

02:32:25.570 --> 02:32:28.250
And we try to present all that
information in plain English

02:32:28.250 --> 02:32:31.430
with a minimum of jargon
so everything is accessible

02:32:31.430 --> 02:32:32.950
for beginners and experts alike.

02:32:32.950 --> 02:32:37.180
I think most important--
And we just don't talk

02:32:37.180 --> 02:32:39.200 position:56%
about good teaching, we show it too.

